"1611","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1553":"1553","1585":"1585","1551":"1551","24 FEB 1549":"24 februari 1549","1549":"1549","03 SEP 1553":"3 september 1553","Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Middlesex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bovey Tracey,Devon,England":"Bovey Tracey, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1520–":"1520–Deceased","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","1520–Female":"1520–Deceased","1549–Female":"1549–Deceased","1551–1611":"1551–1611","1553–Male":"1553–Deceased","1495–1550":"1495–1550","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","14 July 1551":"14 July 1551","20 AUG 1549":"20 August 1549","1550":"1550","1495":"1495","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1611":"1611","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1553":"1553","1585":"1585","1551":"1551","24 FEB 1549":"24 February 1549","1549":"1549","03 SEP 1553":"3 September 1553","Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Bovey Tracey,Devon,England":"Bovey Tracey, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Covey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened form of <b>MacCovey</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cobhthaigh</b> (see   Coffey  ).","English: unexplained. <i>Covey</i> is used of ‘pantry’ in the early modern period and <i>covey</i> ‘little chap’ (a diminutive of <i>cove</i>, Middle English <i>cof</i> ‘bold, eager, courageous’; see   Cove  ) in the early nineteenth century, but there is no evidence to confirm either as the source for the surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffey","meanings":["Irish:","shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cathbhadha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cathbhadh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘battle tent’, <b>Ó Cathbhuadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cathbhuadhach</i>’ (‘battle victorious’), or <b>Ó Cathmhogha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cathmhugh’</i> (‘battle slave’).","shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cobhthaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cobhthach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘victorious’."]}]},{"name":"Simonis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Dutch: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Simon  .","Lithuanian (<b>Šimonis</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Šimas</i>, a variant of <i>Simonas</i> (see   Simon  ).","Greek: from a derivative of the personal name   Simon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]},{"name":"Monis","meanings":["Dutch: shortened form of   Simonis  , a variant of   Simons  .","Portuguese: variant of   Moniz  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":65,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":67,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":100,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Simonis Covey was born in 1520, in England, his father, Simonis Covey, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Simonis Covey, was 21. He married Joanna Bennet on 20 August 1549, in Bovey Tracey, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1520–